questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Infectious diseases can only be caused by bacteria or viruses.
questions.explanation: False. Infectious diseases can also be caused by other pathogens like fungi, protozoa, and prions.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: The Spanish Flu was responsible for about 4 million deaths.
questions.explanation: False. The 1918 Spanish Flu pandemic is estimated to have caused 50 to 100 million deaths worldwide, not 4 million.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: An infectious period is a period of time in which a person can spread a disease.
questions.explanation: True. The infectious period is the time during which an infected host can transmit the infectious agent to another susceptible host.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: If you display no symptoms, then you cannot spread an infection.
questions.explanation: False. Asymptomatic carriers can transmit an infectious agent to others without ever showing signs or symptoms of the disease.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Zoonotic diseases are diseases of animals that, when transmitted to humans, can cause disease.
questions.explanation: True. Zoonotic diseases are caused by germs that spread between animals and people.
